# Wrap and Decode – The Secret Message Activity

<catsoop-section>Introduction</catsoop-section>

A long time ago, before computers and mobile phones, Greek soldiers used a clever way to send secret messages. They used a special tool called a **Scytale** — a stick and a paper strip. They wrapped the paper around the stick, wrote the message, and then unwrapped it. The letters looked all mixed up! Only the person with the same size stick could wrap it again and read the real message.

This activity helps you learn how ancient people used logic and patterns to hide information — just like computers do today in coding and encryption.

<catsoop-section>Materials Required</catsoop-section>

- A long paper strip (about 30 cm long and 2 cm wide)
- A round stick / pen / pencil (your Scytale)
- Tape or glue
- Scissors
- Sketch pens or pencils

<catsoop-section>Instructions</catsoop-section>

1. **Cut a Paper Strip:**
   Cut a long strip of paper — about 2 cm wide and 30 cm long.

2. **Wrap the Strip:**
   Wrap the paper tightly around your stick or pen. Make sure the edges are straight.

3. **Write the Message:**
   Write one letter on each turn of the paper. Example: "ISCOOL"

4. **Unwrap the Paper:**
   Carefully unwrap the strip. The letters will now look scrambled and unreadable!

5. **Decode It:**
   To read the secret message again, wrap the same strip on another stick of the same size. The letters will line up again to show your hidden message!

